properties.title: Williamsburg
properties.description: This piece sent me into a rant. One of my pet peeves is people who try to lift #streetart, only to destroy it. It's meant to be seen and enjoyed by all, so leave it where it is! If you like to decorate your living room, buy art and support the artists.

properties.description: someone said, “why are there no pictures of you in your book?” so, now there’s a picture of me in the book.

properties.title: los angeles
properties.description: maybe it’s odd to be a fan of hallways, but this is probably my favorite hallway in the world. i hope they never change or renovate it, ever. the worlds best hallway.

properties.title: colombia
properties.description: hands and faces and cameras and a sharp, architectural roof. this was the last night of our tour in 2010.

properties.title: new york
properties.description: driving home from the airport, stuck in traffic at dusk. and suddenly the storm broke and the sun came through the clouds, making the skyline look ancient and black.

properties.title: chicago
properties.description: normally this tunnel is multicolored. i had to stand and stand and wait for quite a while until it was all one color. in this case: green.

properties.title: latvia
properties.description: probably one of my favorite crowd shots. i particularly love the graceful arc of the stadium wall at the very, very back of the picture.

properties.title: curitiba
properties.description: i like this picture because the world of humans looks small and dark, and the natural world looks vast and grand and filled with huge birds.

properties.title: toronto
properties.description: i believe she is the nun of the future.

properties.title: colorado
properties.description: flying over america in the middle of the winter just feels cold. i imagine being on the ground and feeling as if it would never be warm again, ever.

properties.title: argentina
properties.description: i love how there’s one very human, natural color on the people in the foreground, and one very unhuman, un-natural color on the people in the background.

properties.title: port allegre
properties.description: someone thought it was an interesting idea to put blue filters over the windows of this hotel. so this is what it actually looked like to peer through the windows of the hotel. it was like looking out at a land of liquid methane.

properties.title: hudson river
properties.description: i could be pedantic and say that the hudson river is an estuary for the 50 miles or so above nyc. it’s also beautiful and wide. i was flying to montreal and a storm had just passed nyc, leaving the sky scrubbed and glowing.

properties.title: hotel room
properties.description: i live in hotel rooms. they are functional. they are also almost always strange and depressing.

properties.title: los angeles
properties.description: there’s so much going on in this picture, i wouldn’t even know how to begin to describe it. but simply: a lot of humans. a lot of lights. a lot of confetti.

properties.title: brazil
properties.description: although it’s simple and decorative, i really like the way the oval window frames this idyllic, perfect cloud scene. it still amazes me that we humans can take pictures of clouds while actually in the clouds.

properties.title: dusseldorf
properties.description: i really like the limited light sources in this picture. the millisecond of flash and the strange box of light above her head.

properties.title: chile
properties.description: flying over the atacama desert, parts of which haven’t seen rain in 400 years. or, possibly, flying over another planet.

properties.title: new york
properties.description: there was this little sign in this weird hallway. it said ‘unattended luggage will be destroyed’, but one word at a time.

properties.title: lisbon
properties.description: the glamor of travel. it’s odd that people look so unhappy on holiday.

properties.title: long island sound
properties.description: the world is pretty simple when seen from an airplane flying from canada to new york.

properties.title: melbourne
properties.description: new years eve somewhere in a eucalyptus forest a few hours west of melbourne. happy new years, crazy sea of people.

properties.title: brasilia
properties.description: the combination of tropical light and oscar niemeyers buildings are almost brutally photogenic.

properties.title: budapest
properties.description: i love that if you take this out of context it looks like she’s kissing a synthetic octopus.

properties.title: glasgow
properties.description: as 1/2 of my family is scottish i tend to see the scots as my people…especially at 5 a.m. on a tuesday night.

properties.title: malta
properties.description: the daily experience of touring. wait. walk. stand. wait. sit. walk. look at back of heads. sit.

properties.title: luxembourg
properties.description: not to sound pretentious, but every architect and contractor is also a sculptor, intentionally or not. this is a hallway and it’s a sculpture at the same time. as if dechirico designed an airport hallway.

properties.title: belgium
properties.description: i rarely play outdoors during the day time. one of the nice things about playing outdoors in the daytime is that the audience is completely visible and illuminated. i was standing in the mouth of a dragon when this was taken.

properties.title: london
properties.description: actually, maybe it’s switzerland. or paris. i don’t actually remember. i like tunnels.

properties.title: prague
properties.description: there’s something strangely intimate about this picture. the photographers and i are all doing the same thing at the same time. it’s like we’re on a date together.

properties.title: iowa
properties.description: farmers seem to wait better than the rest of us.

properties.title: paris
properties.description: again, i really appreciate the photo opportunities created by buildings illuminated by/for the cleaning staff at 4 a.m. i also love the way old concrete looks when illuminated by fluorescent lights.

properties.title: brisbane
properties.description: i really like the simplicity of this picture. just me, a light, and 50,000 people.

properties.title: koln
properties.description: some of the utilitarian brutalist structures at airports are so simple and beautiful. i really like concrete. maybe it’s time for the brutalists to have a renaissance.

properties.title: paris
properties.description: you know, if someone is going to build an insane space ship indoors, well, someone else should take a picture of it. or so i believe.

properties.title: barcelona
properties.description: another picture with only 3 elements. something about reductionist simplicity is very comforting to me. i also like the idea of telescopes looking at an empty ocean

properties.title: minnesota
properties.description: again, i love the pictures that feel as if we’ve left the planet and are in a different part of the universe. it’s possible that for a split second we were flying over one of the methane covered moons of jupiter.

properties.title: vienna
properties.description: on one hand i find quasi-empty regional airports to be disconcerting. but i also find them to be strangely calm and beautiful. it’s like everything has just ended and will stay this way forever.

properties.title: lausanne
properties.description: a sea of people. i particularly like how the form of the crowd reflects the topography.

properties.title: sumatra
properties.description: maybe this is too decorative, i dont know. to me it looks as if our plane suddenly skipped back in time a few million years.

properties.title: english channel
properties.description: i still don’t know why it’s called the english channel, you’d think the french would object...this is in the commercial vehicle part of the tunnel train. to me it feels like the future.

properties.title: buenos aires
properties.description: part of my family is argentinian, so playing in b.a. is always significant. i like the different planes of audience here, how there’s vertical and horizontal audience at the same time.

properties.title: italy
properties.description: flying somewhere within italy, and this very, very old woman was falling asleep in the sun while reading her book. it’s like the sun is looking in on her.

properties.title: london
properties.description: another day off, so i agree to do another dj date. to me this feels as if it was taken underwater in a marine zoo.

properties.title: nyc
properties.description: this is the reservoir at 90th street during a snow storm. i really like cities when there’s no trace of the people who actually live there. the snow on the ice looks like whorls on a fingerprint.

properties.title: geneva
properties.description: what i like about this is the way that the crowd is its own context. there’s nothing in the image apart from crowd and god-light.

properties.title: newark
properties.description: some of my favorite pictures involve 3 or 4 simple elements, like this one. even one other element would’ve cluttered up this picture.

properties.title: desert, california
properties.description: one of my favorite things about touring is looking out of an airplane window and realizing that we’re somehow flying over a different planet.

properties.title: perth
properties.description: this was a few days after new years eve, but it felt as if new years eve had lasted for weeks.

properties.title: paris
properties.description: maybe there’s something wrong with me in that i’d rather take pictures of flourescent light fixtures than people.

properties.title: berlin
properties.description: there’s something really comforting to me about office buildings at 4 a.m when the lights have been left on for the cleaning crew.

properties.title: brussels
properties.description: the amazing thing about crowds is that they’re comprised of myriad people but yet they manage to look cohesive.

properties.title: chicago
properties.description: as i suffer from insomnia i tend to see a lot of cities late at night when everyone’s asleep but the lights are still on. i love the way cities are empty and brightly lit at 3 a.m.

properties.title: manchester
